Here is a streamlined guide to getting a Linux VM up and running quickly.

1. Prerequisite: Create a Resource Group
Before creating the VM, you need a container to hold it.
az group create --name MyResourceGroup --location eastasia

2. Create the VM
The az vm create command is robust. By default, the following command will generate SSH keys for you if they don't exist.
az vm create \
  --resource-group MyResourceGroup \
  --name MyUbuntuVM \
  --image Ubuntu2204 \
  --admin-username azureuser \
  --generate-ssh-keys

3. Open Port 22 (Optional but Recommended)
To actually log in via SSH, you must ensure the network security group allows traffic on port 22.
az vm open-port --port 22 --resource-group MyResourceGroup --name MyUbuntuVM

4. Get your Public IP
Once the VM is created, youâ€™ll need the IP address to connect:
az vm list-ip-addresses --resource-group MyResourceGroup --name MyUbuntuVM --output table

